00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:30.100
We're here in tribute to Primo
Levi, the Italian scientist

00:09:30.100 --> 00:09:33.860
and Auschwitz survivor who became
an exemplary voice of conscious,

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:38.910 position:56%
really one of the first to bring to
a wider audience the reality of life

00:09:38.910 --> 00:09:42.290
within the logger, as he
termed the death camps.

00:09:42.290 --> 00:09:46.430
Levi was an incredibly complex man,
a type of intellectual character

00:09:46.430 --> 00:09:49.000
that we rarely encounter today.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:54.320 position:56%
Intensely literate in literary, his
curiosity equally aroused by science

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:59.330 position:56%
and the natural world as by behavior
and the nature of good and evil.

00:09:59.330 --> 00:10:02.210
He wrote short stories,
science fiction, poetry.

00:10:02.210 --> 00:10:03.960
He edited dramatic
versions of his work

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:06.300
for theatrical productions
on stage and radio.

00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:09.470
And he began by writing
what he called "plain

00:10:09.470 --> 00:10:14.600
or disguised autobiography", about
his experiences in Auschwitz.

00:10:14.600 --> 00:10:17.820
And now, thanks to the prodigious
efforts of one of our panelist,

00:10:17.820 --> 00:10:21.100
Ann Goldstein of the New Yorker,
we have the complete works

00:10:21.100 --> 00:10:24.070
of Primo Levi, which is the
occasion for this discussion.

00:10:24.070 --> 00:10:26.610
It is a collection
of every known work

00:10:26.610 --> 00:10:30.330
that Primo Levi wrote now
translated into English.

00:10:30.330 --> 00:10:32.210
It includes the most
well-known words,

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:35.070
as well as Levi's private
collection of writings.

00:10:35.070 --> 00:10:39.690
In total, the collection spans
three volumes and 3000 pages.

00:10:39.690 --> 00:10:41.190 position:56%
